\begin_layout Subsection
Self-Insurance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that market insurance is unavailable.
 Loss to a person is 
\begin_inset Formula $L=L(L^{e},c),$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{e}=I_{1}^{e}-I_{0}^{e}$
\end_inset

is the endowed loss, c is the expenditure on self-insurance, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dL}{dc}=L'(c)\leq0.$
\end_inset

The expected utility is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
U* & = & (1-p)U(I_{1}^{e}-c)+pU(I_{1}^{e}-L(L^{e},c)-c)\label{eq:18}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The value c that maximize equation (18), 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{0},$
\end_inset

satistifes the following FOC
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{-1}{L'(c^{0})+1} & = & \frac{pU'_{0}}{(1-p)U'_{1}}\label{eq:19}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This maximizes expected utility if the marginal utility of income and marginal
 productivity of self-insurance are decreasing-the indifference cruves are
 convex and the production transformation curve between income in states
 1 and 0 is concae to the origin.
 A neccessary condtion for a positive self-insurance is 
\begin_inset Formula $-L'(c^{0})>0$
\end_inset

 or that there be a net addition to income in state 0.
 A sufficient condtion is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
 &  & \frac{-1}{L'(L^{e},0)+1}<\frac{pU'_{0}}{(1-p)U'_{1}}\label{eq:20}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An increase in unit cost of self-insurance, measured by the marginal productivit
y of self-insurance, would reduce the demand of self-insuranc, measured
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{0}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dc^{0}}{d\alpha} & < & 0\label{eq:21}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a parameter that reduces the absolute value of L' given c.
 Similary, a reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}^{e}$
\end_inset

would increase the demand for self-insurance:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
-\frac{dc^{0}}{dI_{0}^{e}} & > & 0\label{eq:22}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
From equation (20), the incentive to self-insure is smaller for rare losses
